@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"

    @{b}Chameleon@{ub} is a pretty simple utility that serves as a
    Workbench interface to programs that would otherwise need to
    be run from the CLI.

    It places an appicon on the Workbench and (optionally) initializes
    itself as a commodity with a name chosen by the user.Files dropped
    on that appicon can then be used as arguments to the program that
    @{b}Chameleon@{ub} will run.

@endnode

@node USAGE "Usage"

    Just run the program by double-clicking on it, or alternatively
    start the program from the CLI. If you do start the program from
    the CLI, you will need to follow the program name with strings
    which are equal to what the tooltypes of the icon would be,

    e.g. @{FG shine}Chameleon APPICON_INFO=View.info CX_NAME=Viewer@{FG text}
    
    See @{"Tooltypes" link Tooltypes} for details of the various tooltypes
    the program understands...

@endnode

@node Tooltypes "Tooltypes"

    @{b}APPICON_INFO@{ub}
    (default:   'Chameleon_AppIcon')

        The 'xyz.info' file that @{b}Chameleon@{ub} will take its appicon image
        from for this instance of the program. Do @{u}not@{uu} include
        the .info part of the name, it is not necessary.

    @{b}APPICON_X@{ub}
    @{b}APPICON_Y@{ub}
    (defaults:  -1)

        These two parameters specify the location of the appicon on the
        Workbench screen.

    @{b}APPICON_NAME@{ub}
    (default:   either whatever is in tooltype CX_NAME,
                or 'Chameleon' if the tooltype NO_CX is present)
    
        The name that will be placed under the appicon.


    @{b}ACTION@{ub}
    (default:   <none>)

        The action that will be invoked upon any files dropped on the
        appicon. You may use @{b}%f@{ub} to represent the name of the
        file that is dropped, and @{b}%%@{ub} if you want to pass a percentile
        sign in the action string.

        For example, a handy ACTION definition would be this:

            ACTION=MultiView %f SCREEN

        and this would open each file dropped on the appicon using
        MultiView on its own screen.

    @{b}ACTION_MODE@{ub}
    (default:   1)

        The numerical value of this tooltype determines whether the
        string in the ACTION tooltype is

        1  -    Executed as a standard AmigaDOS command.
        2  -    Launched from the Workbench using @{b}wbstart.library@{ub} or
                @{b}WBStart-Handler@{ub}.
        3  -    Executed as an ARexx script using @{b}Sys:RexxC/Rx@{ub}.


    @{b}CX_NAME@{ub}
    (default:   'Chameleon')

        The name that this instance of the program will be represented
        by in the Commodities Exchange.

        Irrelevant if the tooltype NO_CX is set (see below).

    @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}
    (default:   TRUE)

        Whether or not the program should be active or inactive when
        started.

        Irrelevant if the tooltype NO_CX is set (see below).


    There are also two further tooltypes, the presence or absence of
    which will determine whether certain features of the program
    should be used:

    @{b}NO_CX@{ub}

        @{b}Chameleon@{ub} will not add itself to the list of system
        commodities.

        @{b}commodities.library@{ub} will not be opened.

    @{b}NO_ASK_QUIT@{ub}

        @{b}Chameleon@{ub} will not check whether or not you want to quit, at
        the times that it normally would (i.e. when the program is
        run again, or when you double-click on the appicon).

        @{b}reqtools.library@{ub} will not be opened.

@endnode

@node HISTORY "History"

